    "text": "2020 JUN 05 (NewsRx) -- By a News Reporter-Staff News Editor at Math Daily\nNews \\-- Fresh data on Mathematics are presented in a new report. According to\nnews reporting originating in Braunschweig, Germany, by NewsRx editors, the\nresearch stated, \"Based on the representation of rigid body displacements as\nadjoint matrices, the article introduces the adjoint trigonometric\nrepresentation of displacements (ATRD) as a further generalization of the\ntrigonometric representation of rotations.\"\n\nThe news reporters obtained a quote from the research from Technical\nUniversity Braunschweig (TU Braunschweig), \"In comparison to the dual\nRodrigues-Euler-Gauss-Gelman equation, recently reported for affine screw\ndisplacements with arbitrary, fixed pitches, the ATRD is built upon a product\nof a unit line and a dual angle, instead of upon a product of a unit screw and\na real angle. Due to this conceptual difference, the ATRD requires four\nindependent parameters of a unit line instead of five when parametrizing a\ndisplacement along a unit screw.\"\n\nAccording to the news reporters, the research concluded: \"As a consequence for\ncomputational kinematics, the ATRD permits transferring the analytic solution\nto the inverse kinematics problem (IKP) of 3-DOF, general, spherical 3R-chains\ninto a closed-form solution to the IKP of 6-DOF, general, affine 3C-chains.\"\n\nFor more information on this research see: The adjoint trigonometric\nrepresentation of displacements and a closed-form solution to the IKP of\ngeneral 3C chains. _ZAMM - Journal of Applied Mathematics and Mechanics /\nZeitschrift fur Angewandte Mathematik und Mechanik_, 2020;():. _ZAMM - Journal\nof Applied Mathematics and Mechanics / Zeitschrift fur Angewandte Mathematik\nund Mechanik_ can be contacted at: Wiley-V C H Verlag Gmbh, Postfach 101161,\n69451 Weinheim, Germany.\n\nOur news correspondents report that additional information may be obtained by\ncontacting B. Bongardt, Technical University Braunschweig (TU Braunschweig),\nInst Robot & Prozessinformat, Braunschweig, Germany.\n\nThe direct object identifier (DOI) for that additional information is:\n<https://doi.org/10.1002/zamm.201900214>. This DOI is a link to an online\nelectronic document that is either free or for purchase, and can be your\ndirect source for a journal article and its citation.\n\n(Our reports deliver fact-based news of research and discoveries from around\nthe world.)",
