    "title": "New Mathematics Study Results from Technical University Braunschweig (TU Braunschweig) Described (The adjoint trigonometric representation of displacements and a closed-form solution to the IKP of general 3C chains): Mathematics",
    "html": "<p>2020 JUN 05 (NewsRx) -- By a <org>News Reporter-Staff News</org> Editor at <org>Math Daily News</org> -- Fresh data on Mathematics are presented in a new report. According to news reporting originating in Braunschweig, <location idsrc=\"xmltag.org\" value=\"LC/de\">Germany</location>, by NewsRx editors, the research stated, &#8220;Based on the representation of rigid body displacements as adjoint matrices, the article introduces the adjoint trigonometric representation of displacements (ATRD) as a further generalization of the trigonometric representation of rotations.&#8221;</p>\n<p>The news reporters obtained a quote from the research from Technical University Braunschweig (TU Braunschweig), &#8220;In comparison to the dual Rodrigues-Euler-Gauss-Gelman equation, recently reported for affine screw displacements with arbitrary, fixed pitches, the ATRD is built upon a product of a unit line and a dual angle, instead of upon a product of a unit screw and a real angle. Due to this conceptual difference, the ATRD requires four independent parameters of a unit line instead of five when parametrizing a displacement along a unit screw.&#8221;</p>\n<p>According to the news reporters, the research concluded: &#8220;As a consequence for computational kinematics, the ATRD permits transferring the analytic solution to the inverse kinematics problem (IKP) of 3-DOF, general, spherical 3R-chains into a closed-form solution to the IKP of 6-DOF, general, affine 3C-chains.&#8221;</p>\n<p>For more information on this research see: The adjoint trigonometric representation of displacements and a closed-form solution to the IKP of general 3C chains. <em>ZAMM - <org>Journal of Applied Mathematics and Mechanics</org> / Zeitschrift fur Angewandte Mathematik und Mechanik</em>, 2020;():. <em>ZAMM - <org>Journal of Applied Mathematics and Mechanics</org> / Zeitschrift fur Angewandte Mathematik und Mechanik</em> can be contacted at: <org>Wiley-V C H Verlag Gmbh</org>, Postfach 101161, 69451 Weinheim, <location idsrc=\"xmltag.org\" value=\"LC/de\">Germany</location>.</p>\n<p>Our news correspondents report that additional information may be obtained by contacting <person>B. Bongardt</person>, Technical University Braunschweig (TU Braunschweig), Inst Robot &amp; Prozessinformat, Braunschweig, <location idsrc=\"xmltag.org\" value=\"LC/de\">Germany</location>.</p>\n<p>The direct object identifier (DOI) for that additional information is: <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1002/zamm.201900214\" target=\"_blank\">https://doi.org/10.1002/zamm.201900214</a>. This DOI is a link to an online electronic document that is either free or for purchase, and can be your direct source for a journal article and its citation.</p>\n<p />\n<p class=\"shirttail\">(Our reports deliver fact-based news of research and discoveries from around the world.)</p>\n<p />",
